  "questions": [
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-001",
      "stem": "A fair coin is tossed $6$ times and $X$ counts the number of heads. Which probability distribution does $X$ follow?",
      "options": [
        "Poisson, because we count occurrences",
        "Normal, because coin tosses are symmetric",
        "Binomial, because there are $6$ independent trials each with two outcomes and constant $p = \\tfrac{1}{2}$",
        "Uniform, because each toss is equally likely to be heads or tails"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "A binomial setting needs a fixed number of trials $n$, exactly two outcomes per trial, a constant success probability $p$, and independence between trials. Tossing the coin $6$ times gives $n = 6$ fixed trials, each landing heads or tails with $p = \\tfrac{1}{2}$, and the tosses do not affect one another, so $X$ is binomial. Poisson would apply to counts over a continuous span of time or space with no fixed $n$, not to a set number of trials. The trap is reaching for Poisson whenever the word count appears, even when the scenario plainly has a fixed $n$ and constant $p$.",
      "difficulty": "warmup",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-002",
      "stem": "Let $X \\sim \\text{Binomial}(n = 20, p = 0.3)$. Find the mean $\\mu = E(X)$.",
      "options": [
        "$6$",
        "$4.2$",
        "$0.3$",
        "$14$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "For a binomial random variable the mean is $\\mu = np$, so here $\\mu = 20 \\times 0.3 = 6$. The option $4.2$ is the variance $np(1 - p) = 20(0.3)(0.7)$, which measures spread rather than the centre. The option $14$ uses $n(1 - p) = 20 \\times 0.7$, the expected number of failures. The trap is confusing the mean $np$ with the variance $np(1 - p)$ or with the count of failures.",
      "difficulty": "warmup",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-003",
      "stem": "Let $X \\sim \\text{Binomial}(n = 10, p = 0.4)$. Find the variance $\\text{Var}(X)$.",
      "options": [
        "$4$",
        "$10$",
        "$1.55$",
        "$2.4$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "The binomial variance is $\\text{Var}(X) = np(1 - p) = 10(0.4)(0.6) = 2.4$. The option $4$ is the mean $np = 10 \\times 0.4$, not the variance. The option $1.55$ is the standard deviation $\\sqrt{2.4}$, which has had a square root taken that the question did not ask for. The trap is reporting the mean $np$ or the standard deviation instead of the variance $np(1 - p)$.",
      "difficulty": "warmup",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-004",
      "stem": "A random variable $X$ follows a Poisson distribution with mean $\\lambda = 5$. What is the variance of $X$?",
      "options": [
        "$\\sqrt{5}$",
        "$5$",
        "$25$",
        "$2.5$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "A defining feature of the Poisson distribution is that its mean and variance are both equal to $\\lambda$, so with $\\lambda = 5$ the variance is also $5$. The option $\\sqrt{5}$ is the standard deviation $\\sqrt{\\lambda}$, not the variance. The option $25$ wrongly squares $\\lambda$, treating it like a normal-distribution parameter. The trap is forgetting that for a Poisson the variance equals $\\lambda$ itself, neither its square root nor its square.",
      "difficulty": "warmup",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-005",
      "stem": "Scores on an exam are normally distributed with mean $\\mu = 100$ and standard deviation $\\sigma = 15$. A student scores $130$. What is the corresponding $z$-score?",
      "options": [
        "$-2$",
        "$0.13$",
        "$30$",
        "$2$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "Standardizing uses $z = \\dfrac{x - \\mu}{\\sigma} = \\dfrac{130 - 100}{15} = \\dfrac{30}{15} = 2$. The option $-2$ has the subtraction reversed as $\\mu - x$, flipping the sign. The option $30$ stops at the numerator $x - \\mu$ and never divides by $\\sigma$. The trap is reversing the order in $x - \\mu$ or forgetting to divide the difference by the standard deviation.",
      "difficulty": "warmup",
      "source": "in the style of standard introductory statistics texts"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-006",
      "stem": "For a normal distribution, the empirical (68-95-99.7) rule says that approximately what percentage of values fall within one standard deviation of the mean?",
      "options": [
        "$68\\%$",
        "$95\\%$",
        "$50\\%$",
        "$99.7\\%$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "The empirical rule states that about $68\\%$ of the data lie within one standard deviation of the mean, about $95\\%$ within two, and about $99.7\\%$ within three. The window of one $\\sigma$ on each side of $\\mu$ therefore captures roughly $68\\%$. The option $95\\%$ is the figure for two standard deviations, not one. The trap is sliding the $68$, $95$, and $99.7$ percentages onto the wrong number of standard deviations.",
      "difficulty": "warmup",
      "source": "in the style of standard introductory statistics texts"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-007",
      "stem": "A fair coin is tossed $4$ times. What is the probability of getting exactly $2$ heads?",
      "options": [
        "$\\tfrac{1}{4}$",
        "$\\tfrac{3}{8}$",
        "$\\tfrac{1}{16}$",
        "$\\tfrac{1}{2}$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "With $X \\sim \\text{Binomial}(4, \\tfrac{1}{2})$, $P(X = 2) = \\binom{4}{2} \\left(\\tfrac{1}{2}\\right)^2 \\left(\\tfrac{1}{2}\\right)^2 = 6 \\cdot \\tfrac{1}{16} = \\tfrac{6}{16} = \\tfrac{3}{8}$. The option $\\tfrac{1}{16}$ drops the coefficient $\\binom{4}{2} = 6$ and uses only $\\left(\\tfrac{1}{2}\\right)^4$. The option $\\tfrac{1}{4}$ ignores the binomial structure entirely. The trap is omitting the $\\binom{n}{k}$ factor that counts how many arrangements give exactly $2$ heads.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-008",
      "stem": "A multiple-choice quiz has $5$ questions, each with probability $0.2$ of being answered correctly by guessing. If $X$ is the number of correct answers, find $P(X = 2)$.",
      "options": [
        "$0.04$",
        "$0.2$",
        "$0.2048$",
        "$0.512$"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "Here $X \\sim \\text{Binomial}(5, 0.2)$, so $P(X = 2) = \\binom{5}{2}(0.2)^2(0.8)^3 = 10 \\cdot 0.04 \\cdot 0.512 = 0.2048$. The option $0.04$ is just $(0.2)^2$, leaving out both the coefficient $\\binom{5}{2} = 10$ and the failure factor $(0.8)^3$. The option $0.512$ is only $(0.8)^3$, the three-failure part on its own. The trap is computing a partial product and forgetting either the $\\binom{n}{k}$ coefficient or the $(1 - p)^{n - k}$ failures.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-009",
      "stem": "Calls arrive at a Kumasi call centre at an average rate of $4$ per minute, following a Poisson distribution. What is the probability that no calls arrive in a given minute?",
      "options": [
        "$e^{-4}$",
        "$1 - e^{-4}$",
        "$4 e^{-4}$",
        "$e^{-1}$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "For a Poisson variable with mean $\\lambda = 4$, $P(X = 0) = \\dfrac{e^{-4} 4^0}{0!} = e^{-4}$, since $4^0 = 1$ and $0! = 1$. The option $1 - e^{-4}$ is the complementary probability of at least one call, not zero calls. The option $4 e^{-4}$ is $P(X = 1)$, the chance of exactly one call. The trap is confusing $P(X = 0) = e^{-\\lambda}$ with the at-least-one probability $1 - e^{-\\lambda}$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-010",
      "stem": "A machined part has length normally distributed with mean $\\mu = 60$ mm and standard deviation $\\sigma = 5$ mm. What is the $z$-score for a part measuring $70$ mm?",
      "options": [
        "$10$",
        "$0.5$",
        "$-2$",
        "$2$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "Standardizing gives $z = \\dfrac{x - \\mu}{\\sigma} = \\dfrac{70 - 60}{5} = \\dfrac{10}{5} = 2$. The option $10$ stops at the numerator $x - \\mu$ without dividing by $\\sigma$. The option $-2$ reverses the difference to $\\mu - x$, producing the wrong sign. The trap is forgetting to divide by $\\sigma$ or subtracting in the wrong order.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of standard introductory statistics texts"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-011",
      "stem": "A KNUST basketball player makes each free throw independently with probability $0.5$. She attempts $4$ free throws. What is the probability that she makes at least one?",
      "options": [
        "$\\tfrac{1}{4}$",
        "$\\tfrac{1}{16}$",
        "$\\tfrac{15}{16}$",
        "$\\tfrac{1}{2}$"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "With $X \\sim \\text{Binomial}(4, 0.5)$, $P(X \\ge 1) = 1 - P(X = 0) = 1 - \\left(\\tfrac{1}{2}\\right)^4 = 1 - \\tfrac{1}{16} = \\tfrac{15}{16}$. The option $\\tfrac{1}{4}$ is $P(X = 1) = \\binom{4}{1}\\left(\\tfrac{1}{2}\\right)^4 = \\tfrac{4}{16}$, the chance of exactly one make rather than at least one. The option $\\tfrac{1}{16}$ is $P(X = 0)$ itself. The trap is computing at least one as $P(X = 1)$ instead of using the complement $1 - P(X = 0)$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of standard introductory statistics texts"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-012",
      "stem": "The number of typing errors per page follows a Poisson distribution with mean $\\lambda = 3$. What is the probability of exactly $2$ errors on a page?",
      "options": [
        "$\\dfrac{9 e^{-3}}{2}$",
        "$\\dfrac{8 e^{-2}}{3}$",
        "$9 e^{-3}$",
        "$3 e^{-3}$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "For a Poisson variable, $P(X = 2) = \\dfrac{e^{-3} 3^2}{2!} = \\dfrac{9 e^{-3}}{2}$, using $3^2 = 9$ and $2! = 2$. The option $9 e^{-3}$ forgets to divide by $2! = 2$ in the denominator. The option $3 e^{-3}$ uses $\\lambda^1$ instead of $\\lambda^2$, mismatching the value of $k$. The trap is dropping the $k!$ in the denominator or using the wrong power of $\\lambda$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of standard introductory statistics texts"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-013",
      "stem": "Let $X \\sim \\text{Binomial}(n = 12, p = 0.25)$. Which pair gives the mean and variance of $X$?",
      "options": [
        "Mean $3$, variance $3$",
        "Mean $0.25$, variance $9$",
        "Mean $9$, variance $2.25$",
        "Mean $3$, variance $2.25$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "The binomial mean is $\\mu = np = 12 \\times 0.25 = 3$ and the variance is $np(1 - p) = 12(0.25)(0.75) = 2.25$. The option mean $3$, variance $3$ wrongly sets variance equal to the mean, which is a Poisson property, not a binomial one. The option mean $9$, variance $2.25$ uses $n(1 - p) = 12 \\times 0.75$ for the mean. The trap is borrowing the Poisson identity mean $=$ variance for a binomial, where the variance $np(1 - p)$ is strictly smaller than the mean.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-014",
      "stem": "IQ scores are normally distributed with mean $\\mu = 100$ and standard deviation $\\sigma = 15$. Using the empirical rule, approximately what percentage of people have an IQ above $130$?",
      "options": [
        "$5\\%$",
        "$2\\%$",
        "$2.5\\%$",
