      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "A score of $130$ is two standard deviations above the mean, and the empirical rule puts about $95\\%$ of values within two standard deviations, leaving $5\\%$ in the two tails combined. By symmetry the upper tail alone holds half of that, so $P(X > 130) \\approx \\dfrac{5\\%}{2} = 2.5\\%$. The option $5\\%$ reports both tails together instead of just the upper one. The trap is forgetting to halve the leftover $5\\%$ between the two symmetric tails.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of standard introductory statistics texts"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-015",
      "stem": "Flaws occur in a length of fibre-optic cable at an average rate of $\\lambda = 2$ per kilometre, following a Poisson distribution. What is the probability that a one-kilometre stretch has at least one flaw?",
      "options": [
        "$e^{-2}$",
        "$2 e^{-2}$",
        "$1 - e^{-2}$",
        "$1 - 2 e^{-2}$"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "The cleanest route is the complement: $P(X \\ge 1) = 1 - P(X = 0) = 1 - e^{-2}$, since $P(X = 0) = e^{-\\lambda} = e^{-2}$. The option $e^{-2}$ is $P(X = 0)$ itself, the probability of no flaws rather than at least one. The option $2 e^{-2}$ is $P(X = 1)$, exactly one flaw. The trap is reporting $P(X = 0)$ or $P(X = 1)$ instead of the at-least-one probability $1 - e^{-\\lambda}$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-016",
      "stem": "A box contains $6$ sachets of water and each sachet is defective independently with probability $0.1$. If $X$ is the number of defective sachets, find $P(X = 1)$.",
      "options": [
        "$0.531441$",
        "$0.354294$",
        "$0.1$",
        "$0.059049$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "With $X \\sim \\text{Binomial}(6, 0.1)$, $P(X = 1) = \\binom{6}{1}(0.1)^1(0.9)^5 = 6 \\cdot 0.1 \\cdot 0.59049 = 0.354294$. The option $0.531441$ is $(0.9)^6 = P(X = 0)$, the chance of no defectives. The option $0.059049$ is $(0.1)(0.9)^5$ without the coefficient $\\binom{6}{1} = 6$. The trap is dropping the $\\binom{6}{1}$ factor or accidentally solving for zero defectives instead of one.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of standard introductory statistics texts"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-017",
      "stem": "The number of potholes per kilometre on a road follows a Poisson distribution with mean $\\lambda = 2$. What is the probability of exactly $3$ potholes in a one-kilometre stretch?",
      "options": [
        "$\\dfrac{8 e^{-2}}{2}$",
        "$8 e^{-2}$",
        "$\\dfrac{9 e^{-3}}{2}$",
        "$\\dfrac{4 e^{-2}}{3}$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "For a Poisson variable, $P(X = 3) = \\dfrac{e^{-2} 2^3}{3!} = \\dfrac{8 e^{-2}}{6} = \\dfrac{4 e^{-2}}{3}$, using $2^3 = 8$ and $3! = 6$. The option $8 e^{-2}$ forgets the $3!$ in the denominator altogether. The option $\\dfrac{8 e^{-2}}{2}$ divides by $2$ instead of $3! = 6$, confusing $k!$ with $k$. The trap is dividing by $k$ rather than $k!$ in the Poisson formula.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of standard introductory statistics texts"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-018",
      "stem": "If $Z$ is a standard normal random variable, what is $P(Z > 0)$?",
      "options": [
        "$0.5$",
        "$0$",
        "$1$",
        "$0.68$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "The standard normal distribution is symmetric about $0$, which is its mean, so exactly half of the area lies on either side, giving $P(Z > 0) = 0.5$. The option $0.68$ misapplies the empirical rule, which concerns the region within one standard deviation rather than the half above the mean. The option $0$ wrongly treats $P(Z > 0)$ as the probability of a single point. The trap is overlooking the symmetry of the curve, where the mean splits the total area into two equal halves.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of standard introductory statistics texts"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-019",
      "stem": "A machine produces items that are defective independently with probability $0.2$. In a sample of $5$ items, what is the probability of at most one defective, $P(X \\le 1)$?",
      "options": [
        "$0.4096$",
        "$0.32768$",
        "$0.73728$",
        "$0.67232$"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "With $X \\sim \\text{Binomial}(5, 0.2)$, $P(X \\le 1) = P(X = 0) + P(X = 1) = (0.8)^5 + \\binom{5}{1}(0.2)(0.8)^4 = 0.32768 + 0.4096 = 0.73728$. The option $0.32768$ is only $P(X = 0)$, and $0.4096$ is only $P(X = 1)$, each leaving out the other term. The trap is reporting just one of the two pieces instead of adding $P(X = 0)$ and $P(X = 1)$ for at most one.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-020",
      "stem": "A Poisson random variable $X$ has mean $\\lambda = 7$. What are its mean and variance?",
      "options": [
        "Mean $7$, variance $\\sqrt{7}$",
        "Mean $7$, variance $7$",
        "Mean $7$, variance $49$",
        "Mean $\\sqrt{7}$, variance $7$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "For any Poisson distribution the mean and the variance are both equal to $\\lambda$, so with $\\lambda = 7$ both the mean and the variance are $7$. The option mean $7$, variance $\\sqrt{7}$ confuses the variance with the standard deviation $\\sqrt{\\lambda}$. The option mean $7$, variance $49$ squares $\\lambda$ as though it were a normal parameter. The trap is forgetting that the Poisson variance equals $\\lambda$ exactly, not $\\sqrt{\\lambda}$ or $\\lambda^2$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-021",
      "stem": "Battery lifetimes are normally distributed with mean $\\mu = 50$ hours and standard deviation $\\sigma = 4$ hours. Using the empirical rule, about what percentage of batteries last between $38$ and $62$ hours?",
      "options": [
        "$68\\%$",
        "$95\\%$",
        "$50\\%$",
        "$99.7\\%$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "The bounds $38$ and $62$ are each three standard deviations from the mean, since $50 - 3(4) = 38$ and $50 + 3(4) = 62$. The empirical rule assigns about $99.7\\%$ of the data to the interval within three standard deviations of the mean. The option $95\\%$ corresponds to two standard deviations, not three. The trap is miscounting how many standard deviations the limits sit from the mean, then attaching the wrong empirical-rule percentage.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of standard introductory statistics texts"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-022",
      "stem": "An inspector examines the number of scratches on a single large pane of glass, where scratches occur randomly and independently over the surface at a known average rate. Which distribution best models the number of scratches on one pane?",
      "options": [
        "Poisson, because scratches occur randomly over a continuous area at a constant average rate",
