        "Normal, because the count is roughly bell-shaped",
        "Uniform, because any number of scratches is equally likely"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "Counting events that occur randomly and independently across a continuous region (here an area of glass) at a constant average rate, with no fixed number of trials, is the hallmark of the Poisson distribution. There is no natural $n$ or per-trial $p$ to define a binomial, since a scratch can occur anywhere on the surface. The normal distribution models continuous measurements, not counts of discrete events. The trap is forcing a binomial label onto a rate-over-area count that has no fixed number of trials.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-023",
      "stem": "A surgeon performs a particular operation on $8$ patients. Each operation succeeds independently with probability $0.9$, and $X$ counts the number of successful operations. Which distribution does $X$ follow?",
      "options": [
        "Poisson with $\\lambda = 8$",
