      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "There is a fixed number of trials $n = 8$, each trial has two outcomes (success or failure), the success probability $p = 0.9$ is constant, and the operations are independent, so $X$ is binomial with $n = 8$ and $p = 0.9$. A Poisson model would need events occurring over a continuous span with no fixed $n$, which does not fit a set number of operations. The normal distribution describes continuous measurements, not a count of successes out of $8$. The trap is choosing Poisson or normal when the scenario clearly has a fixed $n$ and a constant per-trial $p$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Montgomery and Runger, Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers"
    },
    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-024",
      "stem": "The number of customers entering a shop in a five-minute interval follows a Poisson distribution with mean $\\lambda = 2$. What is the probability of exactly one customer?",
      "options": [
        "$e^{-2}$",
        "$2 e^{-2}$",
        "$\\dfrac{e^{-2}}{2}$",
