    {
      "id": "statistics-and-probability-special-distributions-026",
      "stem": "A spinner is divided into $3$ equal sectors colored red, green, and blue. It is spun $6$ times. What is the probability of landing on red exactly twice? Treat landing on red as a success with probability $\\tfrac{1}{3}$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\dfrac{80}{243}$",
        "$\\dfrac{16}{729}$",
        "$\\dfrac{1}{36}$",
        "$\\dfrac{240}{243}$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "With $X \\sim \\text{Binomial}\\left(6, \\tfrac{1}{3}\\right)$, $P(X = 2) = \\binom{6}{2}\\left(\\tfrac{1}{3}\\right)^2\\left(\\tfrac{2}{3}\\right)^4 = 15 \\cdot \\dfrac{1}{9} \\cdot \\dfrac{16}{81} = \\dfrac{240}{729} = \\dfrac{80}{243}$. The option $\\dfrac{16}{729}$ drops the coefficient $\\binom{6}{2} = 15$, keeping only $\\left(\\tfrac{1}{3}\\right)^2\\left(\\tfrac{2}{3}\\right)^4$. The option $\\dfrac{1}{36}$ misreads the success probability as $\\tfrac{1}{6}$ and reports just its square, and $\\dfrac{240}{243}$ comes from reducing $\\dfrac{240}{729}$ by dividing only the denominator by $3$. The trap is omitting the $\\binom{6}{2}$ factor that counts the arrangements of the two successes.",
      "difficulty": "stretch",
